# Tokens

## Spacing and Typography Tokens

Reference-specific controls for spacing, typography, alignment, and text flow in bibliographies and reference lists.

| Token                      | Description                                     | Default Value             |
| -------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------- | ------------------------- |
| `--reference-spacing`      | Reference spacing (responsive)                  | `var(--content-spacing)`  |
| `--reference-font-size`    | Font size for reference text                    | `inherit`                 |
| `--reference-line-height`  | Line height within references                   | `var(--text-line-height)` |
| `--reference-text-align`   | Text alignment (left, right, center, justify)   | `left`                    |
| `--reference-text-indent`  | Text indentation (negative for hanging indent)  | `0`                       |
| `--reference-padding-left` | Left padding (should match negative indent)     | `0`                       |
| `--reference-hyphens`      | Hyphenation control (none, auto, manual)        | `none`                    |
| `--reference-orphans`      | Minimum lines at bottom of page/column break    | `2`                       |
| `--reference-widows`       | Minimum lines at top of page/column break       | `2`                       |
| `--reference-text-wrap`    | Text wrapping algorithm (auto, pretty, balance) | `auto`                    |

# Usage

## Reference-Specific Customization

Use reference tokens to customize typography and layout for bibliography sections:

**`--reference-spacing`**: Controls spacing between references. References `--content-spacing` by default, which provides automatic responsive behavior (desktop: 2rem, tablet: 1.5rem, mobile: 1rem, print: 0.5rem). This inheritance means references automatically scale with document rhythm without needing explicit responsive variants.

**`--reference-font-size`**: Controls the size of reference text. Use smaller sizes (e.g., `var(--font-size-sm)`) for dense bibliographies to fit more content.

**`--reference-line-height`**: Controls line spacing within references. References `--text-line-height` by default but can be customized for specific layouts.

**`--reference-text-indent`**: Essential for traditional bibliography formatting. Use negative values (e.g., `-1.5em`) to create hanging indents where the first line extends left of subsequent lines.

**`--reference-padding-left`**: Must be set to match the absolute value of negative `--reference-text-indent` to prevent text overflow. For example, if `--reference-text-indent: -1.5em`, set `--reference-padding-left: 1.5em`.

**`--reference-text-align`**: Choose alignment based on bibliography style:
- `left` - Most common for academic and technical documents (default)
- `justify` - Dense academic bibliographies (pair with hyphenation)
- `center` - Special layouts or design contexts
- `right` - Specialized design contexts

## Integration with Semantic Tokens

References work with the design system's responsive tokens:

- **Automatic responsive behavior**: Spacing uses `--content-spacing` which automatically provides desktop (2rem), tablet (1.5rem), mobile (1rem), and print (0.5rem) variants without explicit media queries
- **Typography inheritance**: Base typography and colors inherit from semantic text tokens, including automatic dark mode support through `--text-color-primary`
- **System-wide consistency**: Changes to semantic tokens automatically propagate to references, maintaining design coherence
- **Print optimization**: References automatically optimize for print media with compact spacing and break-inside control

## Text Flow and Advanced Features

**Hanging indents**: Use `--reference-text-indent` with negative values for traditional bibliography formatting. Always pair with matching `--reference-padding-left`:
- `0` + `0` - No indent (default)
- `-1.5em` + `1.5em` - Standard hanging indent for bibliographies
- `-2em` + `2em` - Larger hanging indent for emphasis

**Hyphenation**: Control word breaking with `--reference-hyphens`:
- `none` - No hyphenation (web default)
- `auto` - Automatic hyphenation (recommended for justified text)
- `manual` - Only break at explicit hyphens

**Print control**: Use `--reference-orphans` and `--reference-widows` to prevent awkward line breaks across pages. References automatically use `break-inside: avoid` to prevent individual references from splitting.

**Modern text wrapping**: Set `--reference-text-wrap: pretty` for improved line breaking in supported browsers.

# Examples

## Default References

Standard reference styling with automatic responsive spacing and typography:

```css
:root {
  /* No design token overrides */
}
```

```html raw
  <div style="">
    <stencila-reference>
      <p slot=content>Anderson, J., Brown, K., & Chen, L. (2024). Novel approaches to quantum computing in molecular simulations. <em>Journal of Computational Science</em>, 42(7), 1234-1250. https://doi.org/10.1000/jcs.2024.001</p>
    </stencila-reference>
    <stencila-reference>
      <p slot=content>Martinez, R., Thompson, S., & Wilson, P. (2023). Deep learning architectures for predictive modeling in biological systems. <em>Advances in Neural Networks</em>, 18(4), 567-589. https://doi.org/10.1000/ann.2023.045</p>
    </stencila-reference>
    <stencila-reference>
      <p slot=content>Lee, H., Patel, N., & Davis, M. (2024). Real-time data processing frameworks for large-scale scientific computing. <em>Computing Methods Review</em>, 31(2), 89-112. https://doi.org/10.1000/cmr.2024.078</p>
    </stencila-reference>
  </div>
```

## Dense Bibliography

Compact spacing and smaller font for space-efficient reference sections:

```css
:root {
  --reference-spacing: var(--space-3);
  --reference-font-size: var(--font-size-sm);
  --reference-line-height: var(--line-height-sm);
}
